":"1208–1270","1170–1253":"1170–1253","1253":"1253","14 December 1273":"14 December 1273","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","1270":"1270","1170":"1170","1249":"1249","after 1259":"after 1259","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","14 October 1273":"14 October 1273","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1245":"1245","1208":"1208","before 21 September 1247":"before 21 September 1247","Midhurst, Sussex, , England":"Midhurst, Sussex, England","Midhurst, Sussex, England":"Midhurst, Sussex, England","of Midhurst, Sussex, England":"Midhurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bohun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Slovak (<b>Behúň</b>) and Rusyn (from Slovakia; also <b>Behún</b>): nickname from Slovak <i>behúň</i> (Rusyn <i>bihun</i>) ‘fast runner’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Beachain</b> or <b>Ó Beathain</b>, see   Behan  . This form of the surname is almost extinct in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Behan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Conan, Aileen.","Irish (southern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beachain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>beach</i> ‘bee’.","Irish (southern): perhaps from <b>Ó Beathain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beathán</i>’, a personal name based on a diminutive of <i>beatha</i> ‘life’. Compare   Bean   5 and   McBeth  ."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":1,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":36,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Francis de Bohun Lord of Midhurst was born in 1223, in Midhurst, Su